This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it proposes a framework for Glioblastoma segmentation from multi-modality MRI data using 3-D fully CNN models. The paper also discusses the use of convolutional layers with pre-defined Difference-of-Gaussian (DoG) filters to perform true 3-D convolution, which is a common technique used in computer vision. Additionally, the paper evaluates segmentation performance on the BRATS segmentation dataset, which is a commonly used dataset in computer vision research. 

The paper may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it proposes a data-driven approach using CNN models to learn discriminative image features. 

The paper may belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category as it proposes a framework for automated segmentation of glioblastoma tumors, which is a task that can be considered as a subfield of AI. 

The paper may belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category as it proposes the use of CNN models, which are a type of neural network, for glioblastoma segmentation. 

Finally, the paper may belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category as it deals with the segmentation of multi-modality MRI data, which is a type of multimedia data.
